Introduction¶

Motivation¶

Given that both of us are involved in education, one is double majoring in Human Development/Education and another is a computing instructor for CS outreach programs, we wanted to explore U.S. Education trends and examine what factors influence student educational experiences. We hoped to study the outcomes of these factors and look at what changes can and should be made.

In this tutorial, we will analyze U.S. Education data from 1992-2016 that consists of K-12 financial, enrollment, and achievement data, available through Kaggle from the Urban Institute here.

While it is not a secret that money has a dramatic impact on educational outcomes, we wanted to do an in-depth analysis to examine which categories of spending have the most pronounced effect and to understand just how much of student test scores can really be predicted by purely financial factors. Our dataset does not include information on the financial situations of individual students. Rather, we are looking at how accurately we can estimate scores based on statewide data about revenue and expenditure for each year.

We were also very interested in finding out how the predicting factors and the accuracy of the methods used vary for the different categories of scores included in the dataset. Namely, we wanted to find out if monetary factors were more predictive of test scores in one of either reading or math or alternatively in one grade level examined versus another.

Required Libraries/Tools¶

The following libraries/tools were used throughout the project. They allowed us create visualizations, plot data for inference, create models to draw conclusions, and so much more! Their documentation is linked below:

  • pandas, contains data structures and data analysis tools
  • numpy, a package for scientific computing with array objects and shape manipulation
  • matplotlib, for creating visualizations
  • sklearn for regressions, predictive data analysis, and modelling
  • scipy software for mathematics, statistics, and optimization

Below is a description of each column:

  • PRIMARY_KEY: A unique identifier made from the year and state
  • STATE: State
  • YEAR: Year
  • ENROLL: K-12 enrollment estimated by the US Census Bureau
  • TOTAL_REVENUE: The total amount of revenue for the state in the given year
  • FEDERAL_REVENUE: The amount of revenue the state receives from the federal government for educational purposes
  • STATE_REVENUE: The amount of revenue generated by the state for use in education
  • LOCAL_REVENUE: The total amount of revenue generated by local jurisdictions and municipalities for use in education
  • TOTAL_EXPENDITURE: The total amount of money spent on education-related purposes
  • INSTRUCTIONAL_EXPENDITURE: The amount of money spent directly on the student's indstruction (teacher salaries, textbooks, etc.)
  • SUPPORT_SERVICES_EXPENDITURE: The amount of money spent on non-academic services meant to support the students (school counselors, health centers)
  • OTHER_EXPENDITURE: The amount of money spent on miscellaneous costs not covered by other categories
  • CAPITAL_OUTLAY_EXPENDITURE: The amount of money spent on maintaining capital assets
  • GRADES_PK_G: pre-K enrollment
  • GRADES_4_G: 4th grade enrollment
  • GRADES_8_G: 8th grade enrollment
  • GRADES_12_G: 12th grade enrollment
  • GRADES_1_8_G: 1st-8th grade enrollment
  • GRADES_9_12_G: 9th-12th grade enrollment
  • GRADES_ALL_G: Total K-12 enrollment
  • AVG_MATH_4_SCORE: Average 4th grade math score
  • AVG_MATH_8_SCORE: Average 8th grade math score
  • AVG_READING_4_SCORE: Average 4th grade reading score
  • AVG_READING_8_SCORE: Average 8th grade reading score

The ENROLL column seen above tracks the total enrollment as estimated by the US Census Bureau for the given state and year, while the GRADES_ALL_G column tracks the total enrollment as estimated by the National Center for Education Statistics. Since these two columns are estimating the same quantity, we decided to reduce them down to one to limit covariance in the data. This article walks through the potential problems that can arise in machine learning models from covariance, namely the decreased precision in the estimates of the coefficients and the reliability of the p-values. To condense the two columns into one, we first calculated the number of missing values in each column to see if one of the columns is significantly more populated than the other.

We can see that the 83 rows found earlier to be missing a value in the GRADES_ALL_G column are all also missing a value in the ENROLL column. We debated a number of approaches to fill in the missing data for these 83 rows. We decided that if these rows were clustered together in the original data (close in year), we would construct linear models for each state that predict the enrollment based on the trend in the available data. On the other hand, if the rows were spread out across the dataset, we would estimate the enrollment numbers for a state and year with missing data by taking the average of the numbers from the year before and after, or a weighted average by how far away the reference years are to the year we are estimating if the years directly next to it for the same state have a missing value as well. This article provides a lot of useful information on different methods of imputation and best use cases for each.

Number of rows without score data:  702

Upon visual examination of the dataset, we can see that scoring data is generally collected every other year for most of the time period available, meaning that for example all 4 columns are populated for each state in 2009, but they are all empty in 2010 and so on. We decided to do a nearest neighbor fill since entires for a given state with missing data are likely to have a numeric entry for the same state in both of the surrounding years, and we are expecting this to provide a closer estimate than if we filled in the entries with the mean. We are defining the nearest neighbor based on the entry from the same state with the closest year. This study from the 5th Translational Bioinformatics Conference describes and analyzes different methods of executing a nearest neighbor fill and found that using the values from 2-3 nearest neighbors is the optimal quantity for approximating the true values and maintaining the the original structure of the data. We then decided that if there are datapoints with both earlier and later years, we would take a weighted average of the score from the closest year before and the score from the closest year after, weighting based on the distance of the year to the year that we are estimating in hopes of getting a more accurate estimate. We also decided to seach for values in the original dataset before any rows were removed in case it can provide a closer match based on year.

In [293]:
pd.set_option('mode.chained_assignment', None)

score_col_names = ['AVG_MATH_4_SCORE', 'AVG_MATH_8_SCORE', 'AVG_READING_4_SCORE', 'AVG_READING_8_SCORE']
for col in score_col_names:

    for index, row in data.iterrows():
        if np.isnan(row[col]):
            year = row['YEAR']
            state = row['STATE']

            # Find the closest years before and after the given year for the state.
            earlier_rows = original_data[(original_data['STATE'] == state) & (original_data['YEAR'] <= year) & (original_data[col].notna())]
            later_rows = original_data[(original_data['STATE'] == state) & (original_data['YEAR'] >= year) & (original_data[col].notna())]

            # If there are years for the state before this year, record the closest.
            if len(earlier_rows) > 0:
                earlier_index_closest = np.argmax(earlier_rows['YEAR'])
                before = earlier_rows.iloc[earlier_index_closest]

                # Value present before and after. Take the weighted average based on how close the years are
                # to the year we are estimating.
                if len(later_rows) > 0:
                    later_index_closest = np.argmin(later_rows['YEAR'])
                    after = later_rows.iloc[later_index_closest]         

                    diff_before = year - before['YEAR']
                    diff_after = after['YEAR'] - year

                    # Handles the potential case where the value is filled in for the original data but not
                    # since some of the rows have been removed. 
                    if diff_before == 0:
                        data[col] = before[col]
                    elif diff_after == 0:
                        data[col] = after[col]
                    else:
                        data.loc[index, col] = (diff_before * before[col] + diff_after * after[col]) / (diff_before + diff_after)

                # If there is a value for a year before but not after, use the value from the year before.
                else:
                    data.loc[index, col] = before[col]
            # If there is a value for a year after but not before, use the value from the year after.
            elif len(later_rows) > 0:
                data.loc[index, col] = after[col]
display(data)

These 10 rows are difficult to fill in using other data from Wyoming since they are all clustered together at the beginning of the time period, and there also seems to be a noticeable dropoff in values 2 years later. There are many different possibilities for what the trend could have been in this time, and it is hard to predict a general range of values. We thus decided to fill in the missing entries with the mean for the given year. This article from the Journal of Chemical and Biochemical Data Analysis revelas that mean imputation is generally not preferred but does have a use when the primary goal is not to impact the mean through the imputed values and a more robust fill does not seem appropriate given randomness or other circumstances in our data. In our case, the steep dropoff makes us hesitant to use a fill that prioritizes the other values from Wyoming since it would be very difficult to guage the accuracy of the prediction.

In [298]:
# Find the rows without a value in the pre-K enrollment column.
missing_rows = data[np.isnan(data['GRADES_PK_G'])]

# Find the mean for each year with a missing entry and use the mean in its place.
for index, row in missing_rows.iterrows():
    year = row['YEAR']
    mean = data[data['YEAR'] == year]['GRADES_PK_G'].mean()
    
    data.loc[index, 'GRADES_PK_G'] = mean

Lastly, there are 42 missing values in the column tracking miscellaneous(other) expenditure. Manually inspecting the data revealed that these are all in 1992. We thus decided to use the value from 1993 for each state.

In [299]:
# Find the rows without a value in the other expenditure column and fill them in
# with the entry from the same state in the next year.

missing_rows = data[np.isnan(data['OTHER_EXPENDITURE'])]

for index, row in missing_rows.iterrows():
    replacement = data[(data['STATE'] == row['STATE'])]['OTHER_EXPENDITURE']
    
    data.loc[index, 'OTHER_EXPENDITURE'] = replacement.iloc[1]

In the years 1990-2000, the distributions of math scores over time are skewed left and unimodal, meaning that there were more scores above the median of around 220-225. From the years 2000-2005, the medians appear to increase drastically, and in the years after 2005, the medians appear to steadily increase and become more normally distributed, with less variance from the median. Most the the distributions are skewed left and unimodal, escept for the later years around 2012-2016, which becomes more symmetric.

Visualize Distributions Across Time Periods with Scatterplots¶

In [302]:

There are 25 years included in the dataset, in the range 1992-2016. Thus, we can create five time periods consisting of 5 years each and create a scatterplot for each time period. Of all the columns, we believe intuitively that local revenue can have a signficant impact on scores because a student's performance is often influenced by their local district funding and resources, rather than funding from the whole state, due to the fact that one state can have large dispararities in resources and income depending on the significance of the area.

In [303]:
# Import numpy
import numpy as np

# Create bins for each 5 year time period
bin_labels = ["1992-1996","1997-2001","2002-2006","2007-2011","2012-2016"]
data["time_period"] = pd.cut(data["YEAR"], bins=5, right=False, labels=bin_labels)

# For each bin (time period), create a scattterplot for the mean local revenue vs. mean grades. 
i = 0
for label in bin_labels:
    label_table = data.drop(data[data["time_period"] != label].index)
    mean_local_rev = label_table.groupby(["STATE"])["LOCAL_REVENUE"].mean() # Get mean revenue
    mean_math_4_score = label_table.groupby(["STATE"])["AVG_MATH_4_SCORE"].mean() # Get mean grades
    mean_local_rev_table = mean_local_rev.to_frame()
    mean_math_4_score_table = mean_math_4_score.to_frame()
    table_labels = mean_math_4_score_table.merge(mean_local_rev_table, how="inner", left_on=["STATE"], right_on=["STATE"])
    table_labels.columns = ["mean_math_4_score","mean_local_rev"]
    
    # Plot scatterplot
    plt.figure(i)
    i += 1
    plt.title("Mean Math 4 Scores vs. Mean Local Revenue for "+ label)
    plt.xlabel("Mean Math 4 Scores")
    plt.ylabel("Mean Local Revenue")
    plt.scatter(x=table_labels["mean_math_4_score"], y=table_labels["mean_local_rev"])

    # Regression line to show the trend of mean revenue vs. mean grades
    fit = np.polyfit(x=table_labels["mean_math_4_score"], y=table_labels["mean_local_rev"], deg=1)
    plt.plot(table_labels["mean_math_4_score"], fit[0]*table_labels["mean_math_4_score"] +fit[1], color="green")
plt.show()

In the time periods 2002-2006 and 2007-2011, the math scores look to be more affected by local revenue, meaning that as local revenue increased, students' score performance tended to increase. This reflected in the interpretations of the violin plotted earlier. One aspect of these scatterplots that is interesting is that in the next 5 years from 2012-2016, the local revenue does not appear to have any effect on the score performance. However, in the violin plot above we saw that the distribution of scores was becoming more symmetric during those years, so other factors could have contributed the student performance. This could also be explained by the amount of online resources that students can access for free to improve their scores as well.

Connection to real-world law!!¶

Upon further research, it was found that the No Child Left Behind (NCLB) law in January 2002 was a U.S. federal law aimed at improving public primary and secondary schools and student performance. This law increased accountability in schools across the country, and it resulted in an increase in student performance, which was its goal, by 2014. It ensured that all students, regardless of race or socioeconomic status, would have an equal opportunity for education. This law mandated that all students in a school must be "procifient" by the 2013/2014 school year, which explains the sudden spike in 2002 in student performance, and the higher, more symmetric range and distribution by 2016. This shows that students started performing well, and it displayed that students were more likely to be "procifient" to meet the quota for their state in the later years. Furthermore, this explains why the distribution did not many outlier low scores and it was not skewed left, as schools were mandated to improve all of their students to be "procifient"!

In order to make the columns more applicable to the students enrolled, we found the average for all the revenues and expenditures by dividing them by the number of students enrolled. fit = np.polyfit(x=data["AVERAGE_SUPPORT_SERVICES_EXPENDITURE"], y=data["AVG_READING_4_SCORE"], deg=1)
plt.plot(data["AVERAGE_SUPPORT_SERVICES_EXPENDITURE"], fit[0]*data["AVERAGE_SUPPORT_SERVICES_EXPENDITURE"] +fit[1], color="green")
plt.show()

As we see in the above four scatter plots, it is evident by the regression line for each plot that average scores improve as the expenditure for total, instruction, and support services expenditure increase, which makes sense intuitively. As the funding for education increases, the scores are likely to increase. When specifically looking at math vs reading scores, the total, instruction, and support services expenditure seem to be more useful in math than reading. The slopes of the regression lines for the math scores are higher than those of the reading.

Predictions with Regression Models¶

The visualizations above show slight correlations between some of the expenditure and revenue variables and student test scores. We wanted to see how predictive all of the independent variables would be together and decided to try supervised learning regression models.

This article prevides a lot of useful techniques for choosing and evaluating regression models, and it led us to start with an ordinary least squares regression model to see how it would fit the data. We also decided to use the average of all four scoring columns temporarily in our analysis so that we can reason about the models more generally with plans break down the variation between these columns once we can see how a model will fit the averages.

An accuracy score (coefficient of determination) of 0.21750203188962536 is quite low. It does indicate that the model has some predictive power in that it would likely outperform a model of arbitrary guesses, but we wanted to see if we could get stronger results with other types of regression.

This article explains some of the characteristics of a dataset that might cause linear regression to perform very poorly. It explained that if there is a lot of colinearity in the data, a decision tree would likely be able to provide a more accurate prediction. This article outlines some of the reasoning. The model is estimating their impact on the result by attempting to control the other variables. When two variables are highly correlated, neither will be shown to have a significant impact because when each is examined the model will realize that it does not explain any variation in the data that the other variable does not also explain.

Ideally, we would be able to significantly reduce the amount of colinearity in the data. However, many of our features are highly correlated by nature (ex: revenue and expenditure). We then discussed the possibility of eliminating the columns that we expect are causing this problem and confirming by examining the covariance matrix. However, we wanted to see how each of these features was individually affecting the outcome, and the reality of our dataset focusing on different areas of expenditure and revenue is that we are expecting for there to be high correlations between nearly all of the features. We instead looked for types of regression that might be less susceptible to colinearity in the data, and found that decision trees are much less affected. This article explains how the fact that decision trees are only able to consider one feature for making a decision at each node make high correlations between variables far less of an issue.

Interestingly, accounting for the number of students for the independent variables slightly lowered the accuracy of the model. One possible reason is that some of the states with the lowest populations also are known to be some of the states with the lowest performing public school systems.

When we divide by the number of students enrolled, we are lowering the various expenditure and revenue values by far less in these states than in highly-populated states. This is likely not a coincidence since students in rural areas are known to have the lowest levels of educational opportunity when compared to students in urban and suburban areas.

We considered sticking with the model that divides the independent variables by the number of students even though it has slightly worse metrics because we wanted the model to be able to predict student test scores directly based on the features in our dataset and not by estimating the demography of each state. However, we ultimately decided to return to the model with the original columns because we came to the conclusion that predictions based on population size and revenue are within the realm of our analysis, and it could be argued that these are the factors driving the achievement gap in rural areas rather than the fact that the area is rural leading to decreases in these factors, as suggested by this study in the Journal of Research in Rural Education.

Math vs Reading scores¶

The earlier visuals examining the relationship between various independent variables and the four individual test score columns seem to be more similar for the scores broken down by subject rather than grade level. That is to say the distributions of 4th and 8th grade math scores seem to be closer to one another than the distributions of 4th grade math and reading scores and separately 8th grade math and reading scores. The same holds true for the relationship between 4th and 8th grade reading scores. We thus decided to group the scores by subject and create separate random forest models for each to see how they will differ. We are especially interested in finding out if one subject is easier to predict from the independent variables than the other because that would suggest that the former is more affected by revenue and expenditure than the latter.

Hypothesis Testing¶

We then wanted to do a hypothesis test to see if the differences we are seeing between prediction quality for reading and math are statistically significant. The goal is to see if one of these scores can be more accurately predicted from factors like expenditure and revenue than the other. We decided to compare the resulting distributions from the 10-fold cross validation. The null hypothesis is that there is no difference between the prediction quality for math and reading scores, and the alternative hypothesis is that there is a statistically significant difference.

In [353]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind_from_stats

# Inputting the means and standard deviations from the cross validation results above.
ttest_ind_from_stats(mean1=cross_val_rand_forest_reading.mean(), std1=cross_val_rand_forest_reading.std(), nobs1=10,
                     mean2=cross_val_rand_forest_math.mean(), std2=cross_val_rand_forest_math.std(), nobs2=10)
Out[353]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-1.2818898726958272, pvalue=0.21614726055895933)

With a p-value of 0.21614726055895933, we can not reject the null hypothesis that there is no difference in the ability of a random forest model to predict math and reading scores.

Conclusion/Insights¶

Although we were not able to conclude that there is a statistically significant difference in the ability of a random forest model to predict math versus reading scores, we were still able to achieve a coefficient of determination of 0.8326451858944233 for the model that predicted the average of all four scores.

These findings suggest that state revenue and expenditure are strongly correlated to student test scores. Whether or not these factors are directly causal or are simply correlated with the true causal factors is still yet to be determined, but regardless, the model has still demonstrated that student test scores can be predicted relatively well from basic information on state spending without any other insights about the students or their educational experiences.

It is saddening to see how much of student outcomes seem to be predetermined by monetary factors outside of their control, and this analysis is not even considering the inequalities that exist within states. However, the importance and impact of educational spending does suggest that increasing the amount of money put into education has the potential to seriously reduce the achievement gap between states.

It is also interesting to revisit what was found earlier during data analysis and visualizations: the No Child Left Behind (NCLB) law in January 2002, which was a U.S. federal law aimed at improving public primary and secondary schools and student performance. This law increased accountability in schools across the country, and it resulted in an increase in student performance, which was its goal, by 2014. It ensured that all students, regardless of race or socioeconomic status, would have an equal opportunity for education. This law mandated that all students in a school must be "procifient" by the 2013/2014 school year, which explains the sudden spike in 2002 in student performance and the higher distribution by 2016. This shows that schools were following the law and commiting more resources to make all of their students "procifient" to meet the quota for their state. The success of this intervention suggests that federal government aid and policy does have the potential to be effective in this area.

There are two main options we see moving forward. At the state level, more state revenue could be dedicated to educational purposes in states that are particularly struggling. On the federal level, the Department of Education could allocate more resources and funding to states and regions that seem to be falling behind or lacking in educational resources. Ultimately, whatever intervention strategy is decided upon by federal and state stakeholders in reducing the achievement gap in student scores is of the utmost importance and deserves all of the necessary attention, funds, and effort.
